;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">When Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s Public Investm=
ent Fund launched LIV a little
more than three years ago, professional golf was ripe for disruption. Inter=
national players dominated the sport while many of the PGA Tour=E2=80=99s t=
op pros, like <strong>Phil Mickelson</strong>, griped about various systemi=
c issues. In the intervening years, LIV has hardly been a roaring success=
=E2=80=94it suffered reputational setbacks, was criticized as a sportswashi=
ng apparatus of the Saudi government, and its losses have to be in the hund=
reds of millions of dollars. Nevertheless, LIV has been formidable
enough that PIF has convinced the PGA Tour to sell it a minority stake, pen=
ding regulatory approval.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This dynamic has led to=
 conjecture about the next sport that could see a LIV-style competitor. Man=
y sports media executives and investors suspected that tennis was a natural=
 possibility, given the international diversity among its top players. By a=
 similar logic, others have pointed to professional
basketball, especially considering that so many of the sport=E2=80=99s top =
<em>young</em> stars hail from outside America=E2=80=94<strong>Victor Wemba=
nyama</strong>, 21, is from France; <strong>Luka Don=C4=8Di=C4=87</strong>,=
 still only 25, is from Slovenia; perennial M.V.P. <strong>Nikola Joki=C4=
=87</strong>, 29, is from Serbia; and fellow former world champ and M.V.P. =
<strong>Giannis Antetokounmpo</strong>, 30, is from Greece. Is there a worl=
d, fanciful investors have wondered, where you could convince Wemby to move=
 to his
native France for more than the $14 million per year he currently makes on =
a rookie contract in Texas?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Proponents of the latter th=
eory got a boost last night when Bloomberg reported that <strong>LeBron Jam=
es</strong>=E2=80=99s business partner, <strong>Maverick Carter</strong>, w=
as
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
clJLZ0dVZG43Um1oSzU0akRQR2NHWU9VWT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjUtMDEtMTYvaW52ZXN0b3JzLXNlZWstNS1iaWxsaW9uLX=
RvLWZvcm0tYmFza2V0YmFsbC1sZWFndWUtdG8tcml2YWwtbmJhP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1Jbit0a=
GUrUm9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODElMkYxNyUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9=
SW4rVGhlK1Jvb20rLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxJTJGMTclMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZX=
JtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwib=
Glua19pZCI6MjA0NjE0M30/36d99ccaa3c8222099c2607e237db826b1fb50934df9f92ab15a=
7b5ba44b04ff" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">advising</=
a> a group of investors hoping to raise $5 billion to form an international=
 basketball league. The would-be league=E2=80=99s backers, according to Blo=
omberg, include Skype co-founder <strong>Geoff Prentice</strong>, former Fa=
cebook executive <strong>Grady Burnett</strong>, and investment firm SC Hol=
dings (and its
co-founders, <strong>Jason Stein</strong> and <strong>Daniel Haimovic</stro=
ng>). UBS and Evercore have reportedly been hired to find the money. This i=
s an unusual crew of individuals and investors for this sort of project, wh=
ich explains why Carter appears as the face of the deal.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">The story, of course, raised all sorts of fascinating questions. W=
ould LeBron be involved? (No, according to multiple
knowledgeable sources.) And would this entity be more akin to LIV or, well,=
 UFL? Would this newfangled league <em>really</em> be able to disrupt an or=
ganization that just signed an 11-year, $76 billion media deal and already =
has a large and growing international audience?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">S=
ources close to the group balked when I floated the LIV comparison. They al=
so pushed back on any comparison to the UFL, the
spring football league that acts as a feeder to the NFL. Instead, they desc=
ribed a slightly more modest global basketball league that would mimic the =
Formula One schedule, with games played in eight cities. Six men=E2=80=99s =
teams and six women=E2=80=99s teams would play round-robin tournaments in e=
ach location, over two weeks, with a champion crowned at the end of each st=
op. In other words, the group is not looking to run a traditional basketbal=
l league, like the NBA or the EuroLeague, which many had assumed
given the fundraising goal. Instead, they want to attract a global audience=
 outside of North America, and the best way to do that, it would seem, woul=
d be to entice the biggest international stars to participate.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Very basic details still need to be ironed out, including when the=
 league plans to launch, and when it would schedule the games. Would it com=
pete with the NBA from October through June, or play in
the offseason? Indeed, it=E2=80=99s all so incredibly murky at the moment. =
All that=E2=80=99s clear is that its success=E2=80=94like that of any sport=
s league=E2=80=94will come down to the media deals it=E2=80=99s able to sig=
n. And we are living in an age when live sports content is not only support=
ing the linear bundle but also increasingly the engine of streaming growth.=
 And you can laugh=E2=80=94as many do=E2=80=94but nontraditional sports (li=
ke bull riding or a YouTube star pummeling a former heavyweight champ or go=
lf <em>indoors</em>) are
increasingly successful in this environment.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">The other factor motivating =
leagues to work with the large-cap streamers is their global reach. Ever si=
nce <strong>David Stern</strong>=E2=80=99s earliest days, he knew that the =
NBA=E2=80=99s largest total addressable market existed overseas. But it=E2=
=80=99s a big world out there, and there may be room for a fringe competito=
r as well.=C2=A0</p></div>
